Title: Daniel Skogly's blog | You might not need to store (plaintext) emails
Description: Earlier this year, when I went from having only Facebook-login on Wishy.gift to allow registrations with email and password, one of my concerns was how to implement this is a way that protects the data and privacy of my users. I don‚Äôt have any ads or analytics on the site, the users can select whatever display name they want, and I never stored the email I got from Facebook when a user registered or logged in - only a hashed[1] version of the ID. Emails and passwords, on the other hand, are a whole other beast, and the consequences of a database breach much worse.

Title: Here is a way to predict who is going to win the election.
Description: Take the winners of each of the past two elections, which may be one or two presidents. Place them on the circumference of a circle with a distance along the rim between them so that space represents the Overton Window‚Äôs size. The radius of the ring is representative of the size of the Overton Window. To pick the candidate that is most likely to win the next election, take the point opposite the original two so that when lines are drawn between them, they form an equilateral triangle. Then draw a line between the center of the circle and the third point so that the line intersects with the opposing side of the triangle at a perpendicular.
